[start section id="20112"]

Mr. Mccormick is being referred to Peoples Memorial Hospital to discuss potential surgical options to remove his focal lesion in his liver and his apparent local recurrence in the upper pelvic area.  I spent some time with the patient and his family reviewing the outside CT scans.  The CT scans reveal a mass close to the left ureter in the area of the prior sigmoid resection.  In addition, there is a low-attenuation lesion which is PET-positive in the liver.  I had a chance to discuss the situation with Dr. Durham, the colorectal surgeon the patient is going to see later today.  We are probably facing a multimodality approach here toward the pelvic local tumor recurrence which will likely include Urology as well as Radiation Oncology for potential preoperative radiochemotherapy and eventually intraoperative radiation therapy.  In addition, Dr. Durham would like to perform a colonoscopy preoperatively, particularly in view of the multifocal initial appearance of the cancer.
The patient is cleared for surgery from my side.
I will also have the patient seen by our cancer geneticists in view of his young-onset colon cancer.
Mr. Helms was content with the information he received.  All questions were answered.  For his arterial hypertension, which was again manifest here, I provided medication with lisinopril 5-mg per day.
ADVANCE DIRECTIVES
Advance directive or living will: No, not interested in additional information.
PATIENT EDUCATION
Ready to learn, no apparent learning barriers were identified; learning preferences include listening.  Explained diagnosis and treatment plan; patient expressed understanding of the content.

